            "description": "The Nuclear Pore complex (NPC) is the gatekeeper of the cell nucleus. This enormous protein complex consists of unfolded proteins and shows a mystifying selectivity to molecular cargo: small cargoes pass through, but large cargoes need help from a transport protein. My thesis project brought together two powerful tools in studying the size-selectivity mechanism of the NPC: biomimetic nanopores (well-controlled experimental replicas of the NPC, characterized by running ionic currents through them) and a coarse-grained molecular dynamics model of unfolded proteins. More concretely, I derived an extension (inclusion of ions) of the coarse-grained grained protein model, to provide a nanoscopic view of the conductance process in biomimetic nanopores.",
            "contributors": [
