        },
        {
            "title": "BSc project: Optimizing Photoluminescence Retrieval from GaAs in a Fiber-Based Cryogenic Environment",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 4,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2015
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 7,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2015
                }
            },
            "description": "Using silicon-doped gallium arsenide (GaAs:Si), the goal of our research is to try to perform measurements on the population lifetimes of spin-flips. An experimental challenge consists of distinguishing between excitation light and SFLE as emitted from the system, as these are spectrally close. This problem is made more complex by the challenging nature of using fiber-based optics in cryogenic environments. My project consisted of using photoluminescence of GaAs at liquid N2-temperatures as a diagnostic tool for optimizing light retrieval from our sample. Optimization occured through experiments on polarization stability and power losses on various setup components, as well as performing optimization experiments on the confocal microscope as used in the cryogenic environment.",
